The article discusses the financial challenges faced by local authorities due to cuts in central government funding. Leicestershire County Council, historically underfunded, is significantly affected, with a £19m annual budget shortfall. Despite these challenges, the outgoing Conservative leader, Byron Rhodes, is optimistic about finding a fairer funding system, emphasizing the need to seize opportunities in a crisis.
Pep Guardiola, Manchester City's manager, has admitted that his first season in the Premier League has not met expectations, with the team unlikely to win the title. He vowed to improve in the future, acknowledging that this season has been a significant learning experience. Despite the setback, Guardiola remains focused on securing a Champions League spot and winning the FA Cup.
The Welsh government has withdrawn controversial plans for 10 new marine conservation zones after receiving 7,000 "strongly held" responses to a consultation. The existing 125 marine protected areas will be reviewed for potential improvements instead. The Marine Conservation Society criticized the decision as an "embarrassing U-turn," while the Welsh Fishermen's Association had opposed the new zones, considering current networks adequate.
Boris Johnson, then Mayor of London, announced his support for Britain to leave the EU, impacting the referendum debate and financial markets. Despite controversies, his charisma and wide appeal have maintained his political standing. His decision was seen as strategic, potentially benefiting his future political career even if Britain remained in the EU.
A collision between a lorry and a broken-down bus on the A34 in Oxfordshire injured three people, with one seriously hurt. The bus, a rail replacement service, was carrying 50 passengers who were later taken to a police station. The incident caused significant traffic disruptions as the road was closed for investigations.
Ricky Burns, despite recent setbacks, secured the WBA World Super-Lightweight title, becoming the first Scot to win world titles at three weights. He defeated Michele Di Rocco in the eighth round, attributing his success to his team and expressing humility in victory. Burns aims for future high-profile fights, potentially against Adrien Broner, showing his determination to compete at the highest level.
The article reports that adult social care in England is facing a significant financial crisis due to budget cuts, with a £1.1bn shortfall this year alone. This funding gap, along with previous cuts totaling £4.6bn since 2010, is leading to staffing issues and concerns about care quality. The Association of Directors of Adult Social Services (ADASS) warns that these challenges put the sustainability of essential services at risk, despite government plans to integrate health and social care services.
terminally ill actor and disability campaigner lord brian rix, 92, has called for a change in the law on assisted dying. having previously opposed such a law, rix now seeks legislation allowing those in his situation to be assisted to die, as he feels trapped in constant discomfort. he believes many others share his sentiment and wants a legal euthanasia bill to enable a peaceful end of life.
Police in Northern Ireland uncovered a significant dissident republican arms cache in Capanagh Forest, including rockets and mines, which they believe has thwarted potential attacks. The discovery, one of the most substantial in recent years, comes after a similar find in March nearby. The threat level from dissident republican groups remains severe, with an attack considered highly likely.
The Kenyan election results process has been delayed due to electronic system failures, causing returning officers to physically deliver paper copies to the capital. Uhuru Kenyatta initially led with 53% of votes to Raila Odinga's 42%, but final results are pending amid disputes over spoiled ballots. The delay has caused anxiety and temporary closures of businesses and schools.
Formula 1 driver Maria de Villota lost her right eye following a crash during a test drive for Marussia. The accident occurred when her car hit a support truck at Duxford airfield, marking her first drive for the team. De Villota remains in critical but stable condition, with support pouring in from the motor racing community.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld a crucial part of President Obama's healthcare law, preserving affordable health insurance for millions. The 6-3 decision allowed tax subsidies to continue, maintaining a key component of "Obamacare." Republicans, despite the ruling, vow to continue challenging the law.
Russia's new law regulates social media, requiring popular bloggers to register with the government and allowing authorities to access user data stored on Russian servers. Critics argue this law further curbs internet freedom and expression. Opposition figures, often restricted in traditional media, heavily use the internet for outreach.
Western Sahara has cautiously welcomed Morocco's readmission to the African Union, hoping for progress on their long-disputed independence. Morocco controls two-thirds of Western Sahara and sees it as part of its historic territory, while the UN views it as Africa's last colony. The future remains uncertain, but Western Sahara is optimistic about a new AU committee addressing the issues raised by both sides.
arcade fire revitalized glastonbury's atmosphere, following a temporary shutdown due to an electric storm. the band, along with dancers and confetti cannons, delivered a lively set, marking a highlight of their career. earlier, the storm had caused a brief power cut and halted performances, including rudimental's set.
Mead, an ancient honey-based drink, is experiencing a resurgence in the U.S. Modern meaderies are producing refined varieties, moving away from its previously sweet reputation. The industry is growing rapidly, with commercial meaderies increasing from 30 to 250 in the last decade, and enthusiasts seeing vast potential for further expansion.
Lady Gaga is preparing for her Super Bowl halftime performance, which will span her career. She follows notable acts like Prince, Michael Jackson, and Beyonce, who have used the stage to create memorable moments. The show offers a mere 12-minute slot for performers to impress the vast television audience.
Barack Obama criticized David Cameron for being "distracted" after the 2011 Libya intervention, leading to instability. Obama acknowledged the operation's initial success but noted Libya's current state as a "mess." The UK responded by emphasizing the importance of Libyan-led efforts for stability.
Dawn Purvis is stepping down as the program director of Northern Ireland's Marie Stopes clinic, the first private clinic offering early medical abortions under strict legal controls. After leading the clinic since 2012, Purvis will transition to an advisory board role, expressing her satisfaction with the clinic's establishment and growth. She believes her work has helped shift the perception of abortion in Northern Ireland, challenging myths and stereotypes.
Inverness Caledonian Thistle lost to St. Johnstone, falling four points behind at the bottom of the Scottish Premiership. St. Johnstone secured a 3-0 victory, with goals from Steven Maclean, Liam Craig, and Graham Cummins. Inverness had Larnell Cole sent off and struggled to threaten St. Johnstone's goal, marking their 21st league game without a win.
The Scottish government's Named Person scheme, aimed at appointing a teacher or health visitor to oversee every child's wellbeing, faces legal challenges due to information sharing concerns. The UK's Supreme Court ruled that parts of the scheme breached privacy rights, halting its implementation. Despite the setback, the Scottish government remains committed to the scheme and will address the parliament on next steps.
Neil Lennon has been appointed as the new manager of Hibernian FC, with both parties seeing the move as mutually beneficial. Lennon, who previously managed Celtic and Bolton, is tasked with securing promotion for Hibs from the Scottish Championship. Despite the club's recent failure to achieve promotion, Lennon inherits a stable and talented squad, with the goal of refining and strengthening it for the upcoming season.
The article reports that UK manufacturing activity shrank in April for the first time in three years, due to soft domestic demand, reduced overseas business, and uncertainty ahead of the EU referendum. The Markit/CIPS manufacturing Purchasing Managers' Index fell to 49.2 from 50.7, indicating falling output, with firms also attributing the slowdown to the struggling oil and gas industry. This contraction is expected to negatively impact economic growth and employment in the sector.
Prison officer Adrian Ismay, 52, died from injuries sustained in a dissident republican bomb attack in Belfast. The "new IRA" claimed responsibility, targeting Ismay for his role at Maghaberry Prison. A man has been charged in connection with the attack, while police continue to investigate.
Prime Minister David Cameron aims to prioritize combating corruption internationally during a historic London summit. The event, attended by global leaders and organizations, seeks to address corruption as a major barrier to economic growth and global security. Cameron emphasizes the long-term commitment required to tackle this issue effectively.
Some NHS groups in England are offering GP practices financial incentives to reduce hospital referrals, including specialist consultations and scans. These schemes aim to cut costs and improve primary care quality but have been criticized for potentially compromising patient trust and care. The British Medical Association and other organizations have expressed concern, emphasizing the importance of appropriate referrals, especially for cancer patients.
A woman in China reportedly had repeated plastic surgeries after her husband divorced her for having a "fat face," sparking outrage online. The story went viral on Weibo, with users criticizing both the husband and the woman. The controversy highlights the prevalent issue of plastic surgery in China, with the industry expected to double by 2019.
To celebrate the Jubilee and Olympic torch relay, a Hertfordshire council is temporarily reactivating a town fountain, which was turned off due to a hosepipe ban, by purchasing water from a local landscaping company. The water, sourced from a natural lake, is not suitable for drinking but can be used to maintain open spaces. The council views this as a sustainable solution for the celebrations.
Harper Lee's "To Kill a Mockingbird," published 50 years ago, remains her only novel. Lee, now 84, has never explained publicly why she stopped writing, but her close friend Rev. Thomas Lane Butts reveals that Lee did not want to endure again the loss of privacy and had already said what she wanted to in her first book. The story, set in the segregated South, was initially unpopular in Lee's hometown of Monroeville, Alabama, but is now a source of civic pride.
Adam Peaty successfully defended his 50m breaststroke title at the World Aquatics Championships, narrowly missing his own world record with a time of 25.99 seconds. Peaty, who also retained his 100m title earlier in the week, attributed his success to maintaining equilibrium in all aspects of his life. Brazil's Joao Gomes Junior secured silver, while South African Cameron van der Burgh took bronze.
The parents of a victim killed by a drunk driver criticize a proposal to introduce life sentences for such offenses, arguing it should be considered manslaughter. Chris and Sue Moores, who lost their son Wayne in 2010, believe the current proposal doesn't go far enough in penalizing offenders. They advocate for tougher charges to reflect the severity of the crime and deter future incidents.
Nine British nationals, including four children, were detained in Turkey while allegedly attempting to enter Syria illegally. The group's intended destination within Syria remains unclear, as areas are controlled by various militant groups. The Foreign Office is involved, and the individuals are awaiting deportation to the UK.
St Hilda's Church in North Yorkshire has been struggling with a bat colony roosting inside, causing damage and unpleasant smells. Despite spending £10,000 on heated bat lofts nearby, the bats remain in the church, protected by law. Efforts to clean the church and move the bats have been unsuccessful, leaving the congregation frustrated.
Baltimore's mayor has replaced the city's police chief, citing a need to refocus on combating a crime surge following Freddie Gray's death and subsequent riots. The mayor emphasized that the city's homicide rate has increased significantly, and the police department's leadership has become a distraction from addressing this issue. The interim police chief, Kevin Davis, will prioritize accountability and crime reduction.
Asghar Buksh admitted to killing his wife of 25 years, Nasreen Buksh, while she slept, using a blunt object that was never found. Buksh pleaded culpable homicide due to diminished responsibility, with three psychiatrists confirming he suffered from acute stress disorder at the time. The couple had an estranged relationship, and Nasreen Buksh was planning to move to Pakistan.
UKIP's ruling body rejected a call to deselect Michelle Brown, a Welsh assembly member, despite activists' claims of her misconduct. The party's chairman, Paul Oakden, cited improper process for the rejection. Meanwhile, the party allowed a controversial anti-Islam campaigner to run for UKIP leadership.
A group of cult members in China are on trial for beating a woman to death at a McDonald's after she refused to give them her phone number. The incident, captured on video, sparked public outrage and led to hundreds of arrests of the Church of the Almighty God cult members. The cult, banned in China, believes in a Chinese woman as God's incarnation and has a strong anti-government stance.
England fell short of victory by 25 runs in the first Test against Pakistan, despite a valiant effort led by Adil Rashid's five wickets. After Pakistan's collapse, England attempted a quick chase but were hindered by fading light and slow scoring. The match ended in a draw, but England's performance, particularly Rashid's bowling and Alastair Cook's first innings 263, offered promising signs for the next Test.
Archaeologists have uncovered a 6,000-year-old "eco-home" near Stonehenge, which was built using a tree stump as a wall and featured a primitive heating system. The site, Blick Mead, is threatened by a planned tunnel for the A303 road, raising concerns from archaeologists about potential damage. Experts are urging a reconsideration of the tunnel's route to preserve the rich historical landscape.
egypt's internet activists played a crucial role in sparking the pro-democracy protests, using social media platforms to rally people. the revolution, although catalyzed online, evolved into substantial real-life activism in tahrir square. the movement persisted despite attempts to block digital communication, demonstrating the strength of offline networks.
Edinburgh's winter festivals drew nearly one million visitors and generated over £241m. The six-week Christmas and Hogmanay celebrations attracted 890,000 and 150,000 attendees respectively, contributing significantly to the local economy. Organisers reported that the revenue primarily benefited Edinburgh's businesses, including retail, accommodation, and entertainment sectors.
The fate of BHS, which entered administration in April, is expected to be decided today. A late bid by Greg Tufnell makes him the front-runner to save the retailer and its 11,000 jobs. If a deal can't be struck, BHS may face liquidation.
An innovative DNA-based service, PooPrints, aims to tackle irresponsible dog ownership by tracing pet waste to their owners through a registered database, with several UK councils expressing interest. The scheme, proposed by Streetkleen Bio, utilizes DNA from dog mess to match it to a registered dog, encouraging cleaner public spaces. Local authorities may enforce this using powers from the Antisocial Behaviour and Policing Act 2014.
scotland's sport funding faces a 20% cut over three years, due to reduced government spending and lower lottery sales. sportscotland has not yet decided where cuts will fall, but elite athletes and jobs may be affected. the move is criticized by sportscotland and athletes, while the scottish government pledges continued significant investment.
The article discusses the preparations of political parties in Wales for the upcoming election, with the Conservatives feeling confident after recent successes, Welsh Labour assessing their losses, and other parties like Plaid Cymru and the Welsh Liberal Democrats strategizing their next moves. The Conservatives attribute their success to campaigning on the NHS, while Labour seeks to appeal more to small business owners. Each party faces unique challenges, such as Labour's need to address internal unhappiness and Plaid Cymru's struggle to connect their arguments with voters.
The Fostering Network reports that nearly half of Scottish teens in foster care live with at least their third family, highlighting an urgent need for 750 more foster homes. This instability negatively impacts children's education and wellbeing, while finding stable carers early can improve outcomes. The Scottish government is working to improve early interventions and expand support for foster care.
Historical Chinese documents from the 17th century onwards have helped scientists track the decline of the world's rarest primates, the Hainan gibbons. These primates, once widespread across half of China, began to disappear from records about 150 years ago due to population growth and deforestation. Today, only 26 to 28 Hainan gibbons remain in a few isolated forests in southwest China, highlighting the urgent need for conservation efforts.
Four schools under the Telford Co-operative Multi-Academy Trust were placed in special measures due to inadequate teaching and leadership. Ofsted criticized the trust's lack of support and noted declining pupil achievement. Both Phoenix and Lakeside Academies were rated inadequate, with particular concerns about English and maths standards.
Over a million Europeans have petitioned against the TTIP and CETA trade deals, citing concerns about democratic threats and potential corporate lawsuits against governments. Critics worry that these deals could hinder reversals of public service privatizations and weaken European standards in various sectors. The European Commission maintains that standards won't be compromised and investor protections are beneficial, but acknowledges room for improvement.
Diageo, through its Distill Ventures arm, has invested in Australian-based Starward Whisky to expand into new export markets, marking its second recent whisky investment. This move capitalizes on the growing global recognition of Australian whisky and supports Starward's innovative vision. Diageo holds a significant 37% share of the Scotch whisky market by volume.
Ruskin College, Oxford, is discontinuing several degree programs due to low enrollment, sparking concerns from students about the college's commitment to its founding principles of serving working-class adults and mature students. Despite the cuts, the principal assures that the college will continue to focus on adult education. Students have petitioned to save the English faculty and Women's Studies course, highlighting the college's role in providing access to education for disadvantaged and non-traditional students.
The inquest into the 1976 IRA massacre of 10 Protestant workers at Kingsmill has been delayed due to the impending retirement of the senior coroner and lack of resources. Despite widespread disappointment, families of the victims and political representatives are pressing for more resources and a new coroner to ensure the inquest proceeds. The Department of Justice is working to provide necessary resources for inquests in Northern Ireland.
The Nottingham Castle Museum is exhibiting rare Leonardo da Vinci drawings from the Royal Collection until October 9. The displayed works include a chalk portrait and various sketches, highlighting da Vinci's technical brilliance. With only 20 paintings by da Vinci, these drawings offer a broader insight into his artistic range.
